Roughly a week of build, and their verification lag overlaps with it. Day one or two gets the sandbox wired and the payment button rendering; the webhook receiver and the paid-state transitions are the careful part, because retries can deliver the same event twice and double-marking a payment is unforgivable. The receiver itself is small:

```ts
app.post("/webhooks/payments", verifySignature, async (req, res) => {
  await recordPaymentEvent(req.body);
  res.sendStatus(200);
});
```

Idempotency comes from storing the event id and ignoring repeats. Once verification clears we flip the flag for one friendly client first and watch a real payment land end to end.

Yes — adding an upcoming payout card to the dashboard: the running total cleared since the last batch, the expected arrival date, and a countdown. It reads from the same settlement feed, so it shows the gateway's truth rather than our guess:

```ts
const upcoming = await settlements.preview();
render(<PayoutCard total={upcoming.net} arrives={upcoming.date} />);
```

If a batch is ever delayed on the gateway side, the card shows the revised date instead of pretending everything is fine.

Exactly right. Implementation-wise the export streams rather than building the whole file in memory, so it stays fast even if the client list grows into the thousands:

```ts
const stream = clients.exportCsv({ totals: "lifetime" });
res.setHeader("Content-Type", "text/csv");
stream.pipe(res);
```

Amounts are plain numbers with a separate currency column, no symbols baked into cells — the other classic spreadsheet-mangling trap — and the header row uses stable machine-friendly names so any script she writes against it keeps working.
